    "pn169": {
        "title": "Shared Values/Conflicting Logics: Working Around E-Government Systems",
        "abstract": "In this paper, we describe results from fieldwork conducted at a social services site where the workers evaluate citizensâ€™ applications for food and medical assistance submitted via an e-government system. These results suggest value tensions that resultâ€”not from different stakeholders with different valuesâ€”but from differences among how stakeholders enact the same shared value in practice. In the remainder of this paper, we unpack the distinct and conflicting interpretations or logics of three shared valuesâ€”efficiency, access, and education. In particular, we analyze what happens when social services workers have ideas about what it means to expand access, increase efficiency, and educate the public that conflict with the logics embedded in the e-government system. By distinguishing between overarching values and specific logics, we provide an analytic framework for exploring value tensions as values are enacted in practice.",
