    "pn758": {
        "title": "Research Through Design Fiction: Narratives in Real and Imaginary Abstracts",
        "abstract": "This paper reflects on the value of prototypes in â€œResearch through Designâ€ and considers â€œDesign Fictionâ€ as a development technique. It begins with an analysis of RtD abstracts in the ACM digital library using a corpus query system called Sketch Engine. It identifies an emerging language and structure in academic abstracts on Research through Design. The abstracts frame a problem space, introduce a study, often involving the deployment of a prototype, and conclude with considerations, reflections and discussion. This format is pastiched in a series of design fictions written for the â€œdigital originalsâ€ project investigating new and emerging forms of reproduction in Art. The fictions take the form of â€œimaginary abstractsâ€ which summarize findings of papers that have not been written about prototypes that do not exist. It is argued that framing concept designs as fictional studies can provide a space for research focused critique and development. ",
